{"parse":{"title":"Advisory jury","pageid":27431687,"revid":787739667,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>An <b>advisory jury</b> is a group installed by a <a href=\"/wiki/Judge\" title=\"Judge\">judge</a> to give him or her an opinion during a <a href=\"/wiki/Trial\" title=\"Trial\">trial</a>. Unlike the normal <a href=\"/wiki/Jury\" title=\"Jury\">jury</a>, the advisory jury opinion is <a href=\"/wiki/Non-binding\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Non-binding\">non-binding</a>, and the judge remains the \"final arbitrator of fact and law\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Federal_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States Federal Court\">United States Federal Court</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Legal_case\" title=\"Legal case\">case</a> may be tried by advisory <a href=\"/wiki/Jury\" title=\"Jury\">jury</a> in the case of \"an action not triable of right by a jury\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> When a case in <a href=\"/wiki/Federal_district_court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Federal district court\">federal district court</a> is tried with an advisory jury  the court must <a href=\"/wiki/Finding_of_facts\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Finding of facts\">find the facts</a> specially and state its <a href=\"/wiki/Conclusions_of_law\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Conclusions of law\">conclusions of law</a> separately.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Advisory_jury&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The use of an advisory jury is derived from the practice of the <a href=\"/wiki/Court_of_Chancery\" title=\"Court of Chancery\">Court of Chancery</a> of referring <a href=\"/wiki/Issues_of_fact\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Issues of fact\">issues of fact</a> to one of the <a href=\"/wiki/Common_Law\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Common Law\">Common Law</a> Courts of <a href=\"/wiki/Westminster_Hall\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Westminster Hall\">Westminster</a> be tried by a <a href=\"/wiki/Jury\" title=\"Jury\">jury</a> as a <i>feigned issue</i>. The <i>feigned issue</i> was to inform the conscience of the court, and could be disregarded by the <a href=\"/wiki/Lord_Chancellor\" title=\"Lord Chancellor\">Chancellor</a>. The <i>feigned issue</i> was a legal fiction by stating that a wager contract was laid between two parties interested in respectively maintaining the affirmative and the negative of certain propositions. The <a href=\"/wiki/Gaming_Act_1845\" title=\"Gaming Act 1845\">Gaming Act 1845</a> section 19 abolished the <i>feigned issue</i> and provided that the issue should the directly state the question of fact in dispute instead of a wager. The same abolition occurred in <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_(state)\" title=\"New York (state)\">New York</a> by section 72 of the <a href=\"/wiki/Field_Code\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Field Code\">Field Code</a> in 1850.\nIn Watt v Starke <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_United_States_Supreme_Court_cases,_volume_101\" title=\"List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 101\">101</a>&#32;<a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Reports\" title=\"United States Reports\">U.S.</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/101/247/\">247</a> (1879) the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Supreme_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States Supreme Court\">United States Supreme Court</a> stated \"the verdict of a jury upon an issue out of chancery is only advisory.\" <a href=\"/wiki/Federal_Equity_Rules\" title=\"Federal Equity Rules\">Federal Equity Rule</a> 23, effective 1913, provides in an equity case when a question arises that is triable by jury, a jury trial is held on the equity side without transfer to the law side of the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_District_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States District Court\">United States District Court</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> In 1938 <a href=\"/wiki/Federal_Rule_of_Civil_Procedure\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Federal Rule of Civil Procedure\">Federal Rule of Civil Procedure</a> 39(c)(1) authorized the in any action not triable of right by a jury the court on motion or on its own may have any issue tried by an advisory jury.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Advisory_jury&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Fueur, Alan (June 3, 2008). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/03/nyregion/03case.html?\">\"Bloomberg Claims Victory as Georgia Gun Dealer Withdraws From Trial\"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 21,</span> 2010</span>. <q>Mr. Wallace, 51, was referring to a ruling last month by <a href=\"/wiki/Jack_B._Weinstein\" title=\"Jack B. Weinstein\">Jack B. Weinstein</a>, the presiding judge, to put in place what is known as an advisory jury \u2014 one whose decision would not be binding and would leave the judge himself as the final arbiter of fact and law.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Bloomberg+Claims+Victory+as+Georgia+Gun+Dealer+Withdraws+From+Trial&amp;rft.date=2008-06-03&amp;rft.aulast=Fueur&amp;rft.aufirst=Alan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2008%2F06%2F03%2Fnyregion%2F03case.html%3F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAdvisory+jury\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/frcp/Rule39.htm\">\"Federal Rules of Civil Procedure &#8211; Rule39\"</a>. Cornell University Law School. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20100514160639/https://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/frcp/Rule39.htm\">Archived</a> from the original on 14 May 2010<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 21,</span> 2010</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Federal+Rules+of+Civil+Procedure+%26ndash%3B+Rule39&amp;rft.pub=Cornell+University+Law+School&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.law.cornell.edu%2Frules%2Ffrcp%2FRule39.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAdvisory+jury\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/frcp/Rule52.htm\">\"Federal Rules of Civil Procedure &#8211; Rule 52\"</a>. Cornell University Law School<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">February 20,</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Federal+Rules+of+Civil+Procedure+%26ndash%3B+Rule+52&amp;rft.pub=Cornell+University+Law+School&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.law.cornell.edu%2Frules%2Ffrcp%2FRule52.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAdvisory+jury\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Colleton Merc. Mfg. Co. v. Savannah River Lumber Co., 280 Fed. 358 (C.C.A.4th, 1922)</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Advisory_jury&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation journal\">\"Practice and Potential of the Advisory Jury\". <i>Harvard Law Review</i>. The Harvard Law Review Association. <b>100</b> (6): 1363\u20131381. April 1987. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.2307/1341163\">10.2307/1341163</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/1341163\">1341163</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Harvard+Law+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Practice+and+Potential+of+the+Advisory+Jury&amp;rft.volume=100&amp;rft.issue=6&amp;rft.pages=1363-1381&amp;rft.date=1987-04&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F1341163&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.or